{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"968c985b-c053-499a-9372-b46d8483dc40","content":"Here's how to collect a trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace`:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n**3. Find your process and collect:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps                          # note the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --duration 00:00:30 --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio (**File → Open**) or [PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't on `PATH` inside the container, use the full SDK path or install the global tool via a `RUN` layer in your Dockerfile for future use.\n- For production, prefer `--profile cpu-sampling` (low overhead) over `--profile gc-verbose`.\n- If cross-container networking blocks the diagnostic port, set `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` or use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar for always-on collection.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"445c6037-8d8f-404a-9d3f-ed475ec9ab69","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":420},"id":"64b69d6e-77f4-4fed-ba9e-05c3c09b06c0","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:43:07.402Z","parentId":"5b07f67c-0fcd-45bf-9a6b-5f9270680b23"}
